ler colonialism, and militarism. Amahl Bishara looks to sites of political practice—journalism, historical commemorations, street demonstrations, social media, in prison, and on the road—to analyze how Palestinians create collectivities in these varied circumstances. She draws on firsthand research, personal interviews, and public media to examine how people shape and reshape meanings in circumstances of constraint. In considering these different environments for political expression and action, Bishara illuminates how expression is always grounded in place—and how a people can struggle together for liberation even when they cannot join together in protest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPalestinian ArabszIsraelxPolitics and government. 0aPalestinian ArabszWest BankxPolitics and government. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Middle Eastern Studies.2bisacsh  aPalestine.  acommemoration.  aembodiment.  amilitarism.  apolitical expression.  aprison.  aprotest.  apublic culture.  aresistance.  asettler colonialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107664860 cprintz978150363137340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363210340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632103423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632103/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Packa